      title: 'Cemetery at Zarkten, Morocco ',
      excerpt: 'cemetery',
      description:
        '            <p><b>Summary:</b> <p>Going off the main road (perhaps with directions from local children), one finds a small cemetery at the High Atlas town of Zarkten. Where only ruins remain today, a cemetery once stood to mark the history of Zarkten\'s prominent Jewish community.</p></p>            <p><p>The small town of Zarkten is located in the High Atlas Mountains along the road south from Marakesh. The town of Zarkten is located at a split in a mountain valley where one valley continues along the north-south plane and the other heads west. Two rivers also converge near Zarkten: the Wad Ghadat river, which flows in this western valley and the Wad Tetula (also&nbsp;Asif Adrar n\'Iri) which flows through the north-south valley. Explorer Walter B. Harris visited Zarkten during research for his book&nbsp;<em>Tafilet; the narrative of a journey of exploration in the Atlas mountains and the oases of the north-west Sahara</em> which was published in 1895, and reported a "considerable settlement of Jews at Zarkten." This Jewish community was once very important, but the majority of the community left during the 1950s and 1960s. Today, there is no trace of the Jewish quarter or synagogue, and only ruins remain of the cemetery.</p></p>            <p><b>Sources:</b></br> <p>Harris, Walter B.&nbsp;<em>Tafilet; the narrative of a journey of exploration in the Atlas mountains and the oases of the north-west Sahara&nbsp;</em>(Edinburgh: William Blackwood and Sons, 1895). Accessed July 14, 2014,&nbsp;<a href="http://archive.org/stream/tafiletnarrative00harr/tafiletnarrative00harr_djvu.txt">http://archive.org/stream/tafiletnarrative00harr/tafiletnarrative00harr_djvu.txt</a>.&nbsp;</p><p>Rol-benzaken. "C\'ETAIT LE CIMETIERE DE ZARKTEN AU MAROC."&nbsp;<em>SOUVENIRS ET RECIT D\'UNE ENFANCE A RABAT</em>. Febrary 03, 2014. Accessed July 22, 2014,&nbsp;http://rol-benzaken.centerblog.net/514-c-etait-le-cimetiere-de-zarkten-au-maroc-.</p></p>            <p><font color="#999999">© Digital Heritage Mapping, Inc.</font></p>',
