      excerpt: 'cemetery',
      description:
        '            <p><b>Summary:</b> <p>Raphy Elmaleh walks through the mellah (Jewish quarter) of Amizmiz. Located at the foothills of the Atlas Mountains, Amizmiz&rsquo;s synagogue no longer exists, though the structures of many former homes and businesses remain. These places are described by members of the villages current inhabitants as Jewish owned, but most Jews left in the early 1960s.</p></p>            <p><p>After touring the mellah, Elmaleh walks amidst the scattered remains of the Jewish cemetery, where a gravestone shard reveals a single Hebrew letter (Shin) and a Muslim man remembers his former Jewish neighbors. He recounts how and when they left, and offers a surprising reason for why.</p><p><iframe src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/TUom5cu6-Fk" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong><em>Amizmiz Mellah and Cemetery</em></strong></p></p>            <p><b>Sources:</b></br> <p>"Amizmiz Mellah and Cemetery," Youtube video, 9:31, posted by DiarnaInfo, June 10, 2010.&nbsp;</p></p>            <p><font color="#999999">© Digital Heritage Mapping, Inc.</font></p>',
