      title: 'Mellah at Ait Ferakh, Morocco',
      excerpt: 'other',
      description:
        '            <p><b>Summary:</b> <p>The mellah of Ait Ferakh has been abandoned since the 1960s, when the Jewish population of the town emigrated. The buildings are now crumbling into ruins, although the outer walls of the synagogue still stand. The Jewish cemetery can still be seen outside the city, but no gravestones remain intact.</p></p>            <p><p><strong>Mellah&nbsp;</strong>Mellahs were specifically Jewish residential quarters established by law or custom in many communities of the Islamic world. The Moroccan term, mallah, originated from the name of the salt marsh in Fez where the first quarter was established in 1438. The name entered common usage as similar quarters were created in Marrakesh in the 16th century, Meknes in the 17th century, and many coastal towns in the early 19th century. The mellahs had practical benefits for the local authorities: having the entire Jewish community of a city located in one area made it easier to evaluate taxes and royal protection. While it was usual for Jews to be officially required to live in the mellah, there were exceptions: in Essaouira, wealthy Jews could move out of the mellah, and towns such as Tangier and Safi never established walled mellahs at all. Despite the walls, interactions between the Jewish and Muslim communities were frequent and occurred throughout the city. The physical segregation of Jews was eventually outlawed by the French colonial government.</p></p>            <p><b>Sources:</b></br> <p>Gottreich, Emily. <em>Encyclopedia of Jews in the Islamic World</em>. &ldquo;Mallāh.&rdquo; Brill Online, 2014. Accessed June 27, 2014. <a href="http://0-referenceworks.brillonline.com.luna.wellesley.edu/entries/encyclopedia-of-jews-in-the-islamic-world/mallah-SIM_0014530">http://0-referenceworks.brillonline.com.luna.wellesley.edu/entries/encyclopedia-of-jews-in-the-islamic-world/mallah-SIM_0014530</a></p><p>Rol-Benzaken. &ldquo;Le Mellah et la synagogue de A&iuml;t Ferakh d&rsquo;autrefois.&rdquo; Last modified May 3, 2014. Accessed June 27, 2014. <a href="http://rol-benzaken.centerblog.net/1025-le-mellah-et-la-synagogue-de-a-t-ferakh-autrefois">http://rol-benzaken.centerblog.net/1025-le-mellah-et-la-synagogue-de-a-t-ferakh-autrefois</a></p><p>&nbsp;</p></p>            <p><font color="#999999">© Digital Heritage Mapping, Inc.</font></p>',
